We can write
\begin{align*}
x &= \frac{\cos 1^\circ + \cos 2^\circ + \dots + \cos 44^\circ}{\sin 1^\circ + \sin 2^\circ + \dots + \sin 44^\circ} \\
&= \frac{\sin 89^\circ + \sin 88^\circ + \dots + \sin 46^\circ}{\cos 89^\circ + \cos 88^\circ + \dots + \cos 46^\circ} \\
&= \frac{\sin 46^\circ + \sin 47^\circ + \dots + \sin 89^\circ}{\cos 46^\circ + \cos 47^\circ + \dots + \cos 89^\circ}.
\end{align*}We can see that $x$ is the tangent of the angle between the lines $y = 1$ and $x + y = 1$ in the coordinate plane. [asy]
unitsize(2 cm);

draw((-0.2,0)--(1.2,0));
draw((0,-0.2)--(0,1.2));
draw((0,1)--(1,0));
draw((0.4,0.6)--(0.6,0.6)--(0.6,0));
draw((0.5,0.5)--(1,0));
draw((0,0) + 0.2*dir(45),red,Arrow(0.2 cm));
draw((0.8,0.8) + 0.2*dir(135),red,Arrow(0.2 cm));

label("$y = 1$", (1,1), E);
label("$x + y = 1$", (0.6,0.6), E);
[/asy] This angle has measure $45^\circ,$ so $x = \tan 45^\circ = 1.$  The greatest integer that does not exceed $100x$ is $\boxed{100}.$

